%yoann: explain Window.i field
%claude:
The [[i]] field holds the window's public image---the rectangle
of pixels visible on screen.  This is the image returned by
[[allocwindow()]] in the \book{Graphics} library, and it is named
after the window (e.g., [["window.2"]]) so that the client application
can look it up via [[namedimage()]].
Most of the time [[i]] is a {layer} (a composited image managed by
the draw device), but when a window is hidden it becomes a plain
off-screen image, since hidden windows are removed from the layer
stack entirely.

