%yoann: explain why initmouse needs the view as a parameter
%claude:
[[initmouse()]] takes [[view]] to store it internally in the
[[Mousectl]] structure, so that later when code calls [[readmouse()]]
with this control, it can reach for the display and flush any
buffered draw commands before blocking on the mouse channel.
This matters because drawing in \plan is buffered: before reading
mouse input, it is better to ensure the display is up to date
with what the program has drawn so far.


\section{Keyboard initialization}

%claude:
Keyboard initialization mirrors mouse initialization: [<initkeyboard()>]
opens [[/dev/cons]] (the raw keyboard file), spawns an I/O proc
that reads runes and forwards them on a channel, and returns a
[<Keyboardctl>] handle. The split between a reader proc and a
channel exists for the same reason as on the mouse side: reading
from [[/dev/cons]] is a blocking syscall, and running it in a
thread would stall every other thread in the same proc. Putting
the blocking read in its own proc isolates the stall and lets
the thread scheduler keep serving the rest of [[rio]].

<<[[main()]] keyboard initialisation>>=
keyboardctl = initkeyboard(nil);
if(keyboardctl == nil)
    error("can't find keyboard");
