% important function
%claude:
The loop iterates over all windows, keeps only those whose [[screenr]]
contains [[pt]], and picks the one with the largest [[topped]] counter.
Because [[topped]] is bumped every time a window is raised
([[w->topped = ++topped]]), the window most recently brought to the
front wins. I find it helpful to trace a concrete case with three
overlapping windows:
%
\begin{verbatim}
  windows[] = { A, B, C }           topped counters
                                    A.topped = 7
  view (desktop)                    B.topped = 12
  +------------------------------+  C.topped = 15  (most recent)
  |   A         .                |
  |   +---------+..              |
  |   |         | B              |
  |   |   +-----+-------+        |
  |   +---|     |       |        |
  |       |     |   C   |        |
  |       |  +--+-------+----+   |
  |       |  |  |       |    |   |
  |       +--|  +-------+    |   |   click at pt
  |          |       *       |   |   (* = pt)
  |          +---------------+   |
  +------------------------------+

  wpointto(pt):
    i=0 A: ptinrect? no          -> w = nil
    i=1 B: ptinrect? no          -> w = nil
    i=2 C: ptinrect? yes         -> w = C   (returned)
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
If the click had landed in the small sliver where [[B]] and [[C]]
overlap but not [[A]], both would pass [[ptinrect]] and the
[[v->topped > w->topped]] tie-break would still pick [[C]] because
[[15 > 12]]. The cost is linear in [[nwindow]], which is fine for a
human-scale desktop but would hurt if [[rio]] managed thousands of
layers---in that case, I would keep a sorted z-list instead and stop
at the first hit.
<<function [[wpointto]]>>=
Window*
wpointto(Point pt)
{
    int i;
    Window *v, *w;

    w = nil;
    for(i=0; i<nwindow; i++){
        v = windows[i];
        if(ptinrect(pt, v->screenr))
         if(!v->deleted)
          if(w==nil || v->topped > w->topped)
            w = v;
    }
    return w;
}
@
