\section{Window resize}
% via menu, or via mouse on border directly
%claude:
Resizing reuses [<sweep()>] to let the user draw a new rectangle, then
sends a [[Reshaped]] message.
In the [[wctlmesg]] handler, Moved and Reshaped share the same code
path: [<wresize()>] replaces the window's image, re-publishes the name
(so the client can reconnect via [[getwindow()]]), and triggers a
reflow of the text content for textual windows.

<<[[button3menu()]] cases>>=
case Reshape:
    resize();
    break;
@

\subsection{[[resize()]]}

%claude:
[[resize()]] is almost identical to [<move()>]: select a window with [<pointto()>],
draw a new rectangle with [<sweep()>], and send a [[Reshaped]] message.
The key difference is that [<pointto()>] uses [[wait=true]] here (the user
completes one click to select, then does a separate sweep gesture),
and [<sweep()>] lets the user define an entirely new rectangle rather than
dragging the existing one.

<<function [[resize]]>>=
void
resize(void)
{
    Window *w;
    Image *i;

    w = pointto(true);
    if(w == nil)
        return;
    i = sweep();
    if(i)
        wsendctlmesg(w, Reshaped, i->r, i);
}
@
