\subsection{Reading part1}
% and window.mouseread

% So if client reads /dev/mouse (after it has been opened of course),
% then xfidread wait for mouse events to come by listening to mouseread!
% The winctl itself listen for mouse events on w->mc.c from mousethread


% more a graphical window device.
%claude:
The mouse virtual device uses a ``channel of channels'' pattern.
Consider a concrete scenario: the user moves the mouse rapidly,
generating positions (100,50), (120,55), (140,60), (160,65).
The [<winctl>] thread sees all four events via [<mousethread>],
but the client application only calls [[read("/dev/mouse")]] now.
%claude:
With a naive direct channel, [<winctl>] would have queued all four
positions; the client would get the stale (100,50) from the head.
With the channel-of-channels pattern, no [[Mouse]] value is produced
until the client asks for one:
\begin{verbatim}
  xfidread (worker)                    winctl (window thread)
  +-----------------+                  +-------------------+
  |                 |  Mousereadmesg   |  (has seen 4      |
  | client calls    |  {cm: replyCh}  |   mouse events,   |
  | read("/dev/     |                 |   current pos is  |
  |      mouse")    +---------------->|   now 160,65)     |
  |                 |  w->mouseread    |                   |
  |                 |                  |                   |
  |                 | Mouse{160,65}   | send(mrm.cm,      |
  | recv(replyCh,   |<----------------+   &currentMouse)  |
  |      &ms)       |  replyCh        |                   |
  +-----------------+                  +-------------------+
\end{verbatim}
%claude:
The first [[send]] on [[w->mouseread]] is really a synchronization
message saying ``I am ready to receive.'' Only then does [<winctl>]
snapshot the freshest mouse state and send it back on the reply
channel [[mrm.cm]]. The client gets (160,65)---the position that
matters---instead of a stale queued value.


