\subsection{Writing}

% can move the mouse programatically :)
% but it needs to have the focus apparently and be visible

%claude:
Writing to [[/dev/mouse]] lets a program warp the cursor
programmatically, but only under strict conditions: the window must
have focus ([[w==input]]) and be visible on screen. The write data
must start with ``m'' followed by the x and y coordinates. The actual
cursor movement is routed through [[wsendctlmesg]] with
[[Movemouse]], so it goes through the [[winctl]] thread and respects the
[<sweeping>] guard---you cannot warp the mouse while the user is in
the middle of a window management operation.

<<[[xfidwrite()]] other locals>>=
char *p;
Point pt;
@

<<[[xfidwrite()]] cases>>=
case Qmouse:
    if(w!=input || Dx(w->screenr)<=0)
        break;
    if(req->data[0] != 'm'){
        filsysrespond(x->fs, x, &fc, Ebadmouse);
        return;
    }
    p = nil;
    pt.x = strtoul(req->data+1, &p, 0);
    if(p == nil){
        filsysrespond(x->fs, x, &fc, Eshort);
        return;
    }
    pt.y = strtoul(p, nil, 0);
    if(w==input && wpointto(mouse->xy)==w)
        wsendctlmesg(w, Movemouse, Rpt(pt, pt), nil);
    break;
@



