\subsection{Frame colors}

%claude:
The frame uses five colors indexed by [[BACK]], [[HIGH]], [[BORD]],
[[TEXT]], and [[HTEXT]]:
\begin{itemize}
\item [[BACK]] (white): normal text background.
\item [[HIGH]] (light grey, [[0xCCCCCC]]): background of selected text.
\item [[BORD]] (medium grey, [[0x999999]]): scrollbar and border fill.
\item [[TEXT]] (black): normal text foreground.
\item [[HTEXT]] (black): selected text foreground (same as TEXT in [[rio]]).
\end{itemize}
%claude:
The key visual trick is that when a window loses focus, [<wsetcols>]
swaps the text color from black to dark grey ([[0x666666]]), giving the
``inactive window'' appearance without changing any content---only the
colors in [[frm.cols]] are modified, followed by a [<frredraw()>].
This is a lightweight way to indicate which window has keyboard focus.

