%******************************************************************************
\chapter{Error Management}
%******************************************************************************
\label{chap:error}

%claude:
[[rio]]'s error strings are all lowercase, terse, and stored as
global [[char]] arrays because they cross a {9P protocol boundary}:
when [<filsysrespond()>] is called with an error, the string is
copied into an [[Rerror]] message and sent back through the pipe
to the client's kernel, which in turn reports it via the client's
[[errstr()]] or [[%r]] format. The conventions match those of
other \plan fileservers (e.g., ``permission denied'',
``file does not exist''), which means a client program written
to expect \plan-style error reporting can display rio-produced
errors without knowing they came from [[rio]] specifically.

